Although the real count of American dead in Iraq passed 1000 some time ago , today the "official" count hit 1000, as readers undoubtedly know by now. And, once again, Left I on the News takes this opportunity to reiterate the obvious - U.S. troops must leave Iraq now . Not four years from now, not six months from now, not after they are replaced by U.N. troops, not after the situation has "stabilized," but now .

There are many Americans who opposed, or at least now oppose, the invasion and occupation of Iraq, but still think the "out now" position is "unrealistic," that "we" have to "finish the job," that an American pullout now will see Iraq descend into chaos with Iraqis dying left and right. And, again as Left I has noted before, whatever happens after American troops leave couldn't possibly be as bad for Iraqis as what is happening to them right now.

Here are the headlines from from just the last few days :
Item : "US Marines Say Up To 100 Insurgents Killed In Fallujah Air Strikes"
Item : "40 killed in clashes in Sadr City"
Item : "American forces arrest Ezzat al-Douri [sic], 70 men were killed trying to rescue him" That's all on top of the hundreds killed in Najaf recently, and countless (and uncounted) more killed day after day in cities across Iraq..

Some will say it is "unrealistic" to say "out now" because neither Bush nor Kerry (or even Nader, for that matter) are for that position. And that's true. The American people don't get a chance to vote for war, neither to start wars nor to end them. Only constant pressure from people opposed to the war and occupation can do that. Demonstrations, speakouts, actions, letters to the editor, talking to our neighbors, and in short doing everything we can to raise the din of voices shouting "out now" will ever accomplish that goal. So get started (or keep going)!
